<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920107-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>920107-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Baker Hughes to Buy   Sonat Services Unit   For Up to $360 Million</HL><DATE>01/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   BHI SNT</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-EQUIPMENT, SERVICES, PLATFORM SUPPLIERS (EQS)OIL-EQUIPMENT AND SERVICES (OIE)PETROLEUM (PET)PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>ALABAMA (AL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   HOUSTON -- Baker Hughes Inc. said it agreed to purchase anoil-field services unit from Sonat Inc. for a total of asmuch $360 million in cash and preferred stock, as well ascertain royalty considerations.   Baker Hughes, an oil and gas service company, said it willbuy Teleco Oilfield Services Inc. from Sonat, a natural-gaspipeline concern based in Birmingham, Ala. In addition to$200 million in cash, Baker will pay Sonat four millionshares of convertible preferred stock and a 5% royalty forfive years on revenue derived from drilling-system technologyrecently developed by Teleco.</LP><TEXT>   The preferred stock is convertible at $32.50 a share ofBaker Hughes common stock, subject to adjustment at closing.Baker Hughes said that at the current share price for itscommon stock, the preferred stock has an indicated marketvalue of between $140 million and $160 million. Baker Hughescurrently has about 138.4 million common shares outstanding.   The royalties are payable on revenue from Teleco'sdirectional and formation evaluation measurement system. ABaker Hughes spokesman said the system is useful whendrilling deviates from the initial vertical hole, especiallyin increasingly common horizontal drilling projects. Thesystem provides feedback to the driller on the exact locationof the drill bit and other information about the formationduring the drilling process, the spokesman said.   In late New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday, BakerHughes shares rose 37.5 cent to $20.50, and Sonat shares fell25 cents to $35.50.</TEXT></DOC>